Exactly. Instead of registering the full flower GLB, I create an invisible cylinder — 0.3m radius, 1m tall, centered at the flower's base. That's the stem collider. Dorothy bumps against it at shin-to-waist height, but the petals above are non-collidable. She walks under canopies freely.

```js
const stemCollider = new THREE.Mesh(
    new THREE.CylinderGeometry(0.3, 0.3, 1.0, 6),
    new THREE.MeshBasicMaterial({ visible: false })
);
stemCollider.position.set(fx, 0.5, fz);
groundedPlayer.register(stemCollider);
```

This is a universal pattern in game physics: collision geometry is separate from visual geometry. The beautiful flower mesh is for rendering. The invisible cylinder is for physics. They occupy the same space but serve different purposes.
